We require that the composition $T \circ S$ be the zero transformation, which in matrix form is $BA = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}$. For each option, we compute the matrix product $BA$ and check whether it equals the zero matrix, ensuring that both $A$ and $B$ are non-zero matrices.

Option A:
$$
B = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 1 \\ 1 & 1\end{pmatrix},\quad A = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 1 \\ -1 & -1\end{pmatrix}
$$
$$
BA = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 1 \\ 1 & 1\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}1 & 1 \\ -1 & -1\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}1\cdot 1 + 1\cdot(-1) & 1\cdot 1 + 1\cdot(-1) \\ 1\cdot 1 + 1\cdot(-1) & 1\cdot 1 + 1\cdot(-1)\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
$$
Both $A$ and $B$ are non-zero, so A satisfies the condition.

Option B:
$$
B = \begin{pmatrix}1 & -1 \\ -1 & 1\end{pmatrix},\quad A = \begin{pmatrix}2 & 1 \\ 1 & 1\end{pmatrix}
$$
$$
BA = \begin{pmatrix}1 & -1 \\ -1 & 1\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}2 & 1 \\ 1 & 1\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}1\cdot 2 + (-1)\cdot 1 & 1\cdot 1 + (-1)\cdot 1 \\ (-1)\cdot 2 + 1\cdot 1 & (-1)\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 1\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ -1 & 0\end{pmatrix}
$$
This is not the zero matrix, so B does not satisfy the condition.

Option C:
$$
B = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 \\ 0 & 1\end{pmatrix},\quad A = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
$$
$$
BA = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 \\ 0 & 1\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}0\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 0 & 0\cdot 0 + 1\cdot 0 \\ 0\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 0 & 0\cdot 0 + 1\cdot 0\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
$$
Both $A$ and $B$ are non-zero, so C satisfies the condition.

Option D:
$$
B = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\ 1 & 1\end{pmatrix},\quad A = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1\end{pmatrix}
$$
Since $A$ is the identity matrix, $BA = B = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\ 1 & 1\end{pmatrix}$.
This is not the zero matrix, so D does not satisfy the condition.

Option E:
$$
B = \begin{pmatrix}4 & -2 \\ -3 & 1\end{pmatrix},\quad A = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 \\ 3 & 4\end{pmatrix}
$$
$$
BA = \begin{pmatrix}4 & -2 \\ -3 & 1\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 \\ 3 & 4\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}4\cdot 1 + (-2)\cdot 3 & 4\cdot 2 + (-2)\cdot 4 \\ (-3)\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 3 & (-3)\cdot 2 + 1\cdot 4\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}-2 & 0 \\ 0 & -2\end{pmatrix}
$$
This is not the zero matrix, so E does not satisfy the condition.

Therefore, the pairs that satisfy $BA = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}$ are A and C.
